Teachers with Masters Degreee - District Wise

This plot is regarding the percentage of teacherrs with masters degreee in each district. From the plot we can also interpret the change in teachers who have masters degree.

library(ggplot2)
#install.packages("moments")
library(moments)
#install.packages("ggplot2")
library(readxl)
#library(ggplot2)
q2 <- readxl::read_xlsx("Master.xlsx")
pl2 <- ggplot(q2,aes(x=q2$`School Year`,y=q2$`Teachers with Masters Degree`))+geom_point() + facet_wrap(~q2$`Agency Name`)
pl2 + labs(title="Teachers with Master's Degree - District wise",x="Year", y="% of Teachers with masters degree" ) + theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 20, face = "bold",color = "purple4"),axis.title.x = element_text(vjust = 10,size = 15),axis.title.y = element_text(size = 15))

Attendance Rate vs Dropout Rate

In this plot, i had used ggplot to obtain plot on Attendance rate vs Dropout Rate. We can interpret that the attendance had an impact on the dropout rate which is known fact. The lower the absence percecntage the lower was the dropout rate.

q4 <- readxl::read_xlsx("ques 2.xlsx")
pl3 <- ggplot(q4,aes(x=`Attendance Rate`,y=`Dropout Rate`))
pl3.1 <- pl3 + geom_point(aes(color=`Attendance Rate`)) + geom_smooth()
pl3.1 + labs(title="Attendance Rate vs Dropout Rate") +theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 20, face = "bold",color = "brown3"),axis.title.x = element_text(vjust = 10,size = 15),axis.title.y = element_text(size = 15))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess'

## Including Plots

## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess'

## Attendance Rate vs Dropout Rate - District Wise So in this pot we can figure out the district wise performance of schools and how the attendance rate had impact on their dropout rate.

q4 <- readxl::read_xlsx("ques 2.xlsx")
pl4 <- ggplot(q4,aes(q4$`Attendance Rate`,q4$`Dropout Rate`)) + geom_point() + facet_wrap(~q4$`Agency Name`)
pl4.1 <- pl4 + labs(title="Attendance Rate vs Dropout Rate", x="Attendance Rate", y="Dropout Rate") +theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 20, face = "bold",color = "orangered1"),axis.title.x = element_text(vjust = 10,size = 15),axis.title.y = element_text(size = 15))

Data cleaning

Graduation <- read_excel("D:/Downloads/Fall 2017/DTD/Set4Final.xlsx")

Graduation[Graduation == '-1'] <- NA
View(Graduation)

Grad <- na.omit(Graduation)
summary(Grad)

GradCln <- Gradset
View(GradCln)

Grouping the demographics into subsets

Gender <- GradCln[GradCln$Description == "Male" | GradCln$Description == "Female",]

Ethnic <- GradCln[GradCln$Description == "Ethnic7 - Hispanic" | GradCln$Description == "Ethnic7 - American Indian/Alaska Native" | GradCln$Description == "Ethnic7 - Asian" | GradCln$Description == "Ethnic7 - Black or African American" | GradCln$Description == "Ethnic7 - Native Hawaiian or Other Pacific Islander" | GradCln$Description == "Ethnic7 - Black or African American" | GradCln$Description == "Ethnic7 - White" | GradCln$Description == "Ethnic7 - Two or More Races",]

Others <- GradCln[GradCln$Description == "Students eligible for free and reduced lunch" | GradCln$Description == "Special Education Students" | GradCln$Description == "English Language Learners",]

Plots for graduation percentage based on ethnicity

attach(Ethnic)

P5.1 <- ggplot(Ethnic, aes(x = Description, y = `Graduation Percentage`)) + theme(legend.position = "right", axis.text = element_text(size = 6))

P6.1 <- P5.1 + geom_point(aes(color = `Graduation Cohort`), alpha = 0.5, size = 1.5, position = position_jitter(width = 0.25, height = 0))

P6.1 + scale_color_continuous(name="Years")

Plots for graduation percentage based on gender

attach(Others)
## The following objects are masked from Ethnic:
## 
##     Description, Graduation Cohort, Graduation Percentage, Type
P1.1<- ggplot(Others, aes(x = `Description`, y = `Graduation Percentage`)) + theme(legend.position = "top", axis.text = element_text(size = 6))

P2.1 <- P1.1 + geom_point(aes(color = `Graduation Cohort`), alpha = 0.5, size = 1.5, position = position_jitter(width = 0.25, height = 0))

# Renamed the years and used different colours to differentiate between low and high values

P2.1 + scale_color_continuous(name="Years",breaks=c(2011, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015, 2016),labels = c("'11", "'12", "'13", "'14", "'15", "'16"),low = "orange", high = "black")

Plots for graduation percentage based on gender

attach(Gender)
## The following objects are masked from Others:
## 
##     Description, Graduation Cohort, Graduation Percentage, Type
## The following objects are masked from Ethnic:
## 
##     Description, Graduation Cohort, Graduation Percentage, Type
P3.1 <- ggplot(Gender, aes(x = Description, y = `Graduation Percentage`)) + theme(legend.position = "right", axis.text = element_text(size = 6))

P4.1 <- P3.1 + geom_point(aes(color = `Graduation Cohort`), alpha = 0.5, size = 1.5, position = position_jitter(width = 0.25, height = 0))

P4.1 + scale_color_continuous(name="Years",low="Pink", high = "Black")
